Installation / Usage Guide via jsDelivr workflow
Because this is compiled to a clean UMD module without any .js file dependencies, anyone can use it by simply injecting it via a script tag.

1. HTML Drop-in Method
code
Html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <!-- Load the library -->
    <script src="path/to/x-frame-titan.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- 
      Simply use the standard iframe tag with the `is` attribute. 
      mode="virtual" (default) applies the True Bypass mechanism.
      mode="cloak" falls back to Google Translate proxy.
    -->
    <iframe is="x-frame-bypass" 
            src="https://google.com" 
            mode="virtual" 
            theme="#ff0000" 
            style="width:100vw; height:100vh;">
    </iframe>

</body>
</html>
2. Programmatic JavaScript Method
code
JavaScript
// Create Titan element programmatically
const titanFrame = document.createElement('iframe', { is: 'x-frame-bypass' });

// Add event listeners (Custom API)
titanFrame.addEventListener('titan-load-start', (e) => console.log('Loading:', e.detail.url));
titanFrame.addEventListener('titan-load-complete', (e) => console.log('Done:', e.detail.url));

// Inject into DOM
document.body.appendChild(titanFrame);

// Command the Virtual Browser API
titanFrame.navigate('https://cnn.com');
The "Better Algorithm" Breakthroughs detailed:
The In-Context Network Overrider (<script id="titan-interceptor">): Earlier versions would fail if the embedded page utilized React, Angular, or standard vanilla JS fetching fetch('/api/users'). This new version overrides the native network prototype inside the iframe itself, converting local XHR/Fetch paths to full paths routed through the external Gateway Swarm.

PostMessage Architecture (window.parent.postMessage({ type: 'TITAN_NAVIGATE'... })): Instead of clicking a link and letting the iframe navigate normally (which throws CORS tracking errors), click events are caught matching <a> tags, neutralized via e.preventDefault(), and pushed to the global wrapper. The parent class then takes the target URL and repeats the gateway-swarm routing securely over it.
